SIMPLE: see
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: See
<hw>See</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>se</ets>,
<ets>see</ets>, OF. <ets>se</ets>, <ets>sed</ets>, <ets>sied</ets>, fr.
L. <ets>sedes</ets> a seat, or the kindred <ets>sedere</ets> to sit. See
<er>Sit</er>, and cf. <er>Siege</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A seat; a
site; a place where sovereign power is exercised.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Jove laughed on Venus from his sovereign <qex>see</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The seat
of episcopal power; a diocese; the jurisdiction of a bishop; <as>as, the
<ex>see</ex> of New York</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The seat of an
archbishop; a province or jurisdiction of an archbishop; <as>as, an
archiepiscopal <ex>see</ex></as>.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The seat,
place, or office of the pope, or Roman pontiff; <as>as, the papal
<ex>see</ex></as>.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>The pope or his court at
Rome; <as>as, to appeal to the <ex>see</ex> of Rome</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Apostolic see</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Apostolic</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1303 pr=PCP --></p>

<p><ent>See</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: See
<hw>See</hw> <pr>(s⟦emac⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Saw</conjf> <pr>(s⟦add⟧)</pr>; <pos>p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Seen</conjf> <pr>(s⟦emac⟧n)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Seeing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>seen</ets>,
<ets>sen</ets>, <ets>seon</ets>, AS. <ets>se⟦oacute⟧n</ets>; akin to
OFries. <ets>s⟦imac⟧a</ets>, D. <ets>zien</ets>, OS. & OHG.
<ets>sehan</ets>, G. <ets>sehen</ets>, Icel. <ets>sj⟦amac⟧</ets>, Sw.
<ets>se</ets>, Dan. <ets>see</ets>, Goth. <ets>sa⟦iacute⟧hwan</ets>, and
probably to L. <ets>sequi</ets> to follow (and so originally meaning, to
follow with the eyes). Gr. <grk>"e`pesqai</grk>, Skr. <ets>sac</ets>.
Cf. <er>Sight</er>, <er>Sue</er> to follow.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
perceive by the eye; to have knowledge of the existence and apparent
qualities of by the organs of sight; to behold; to descry; to
view.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will now turn aside, and <qex>see</qex> this great sight.</q>
<rj><qau>Ex. iii. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To perceive by mental vision; to form an idea or
conception of; to note with the mind; to observe; to discern; to
distinguish; to understand; to comprehend; to ascertain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Go, I pray thee, <qex>see</qex> whether it be well with thy
brethren.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xxxvii. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Jesus <qex>saw</qex> that he answered discreetly.</q>
<rj><qau>Mark xii. 34.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who's so gross⟦br⟧
That <qex>seeth</qex> not this palpable device?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To follow with the eyes, or as with the eyes; to
watch; to regard attentively; to look after.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I had a mind to <qex>see</qex> him out, and therefore did not care
for contradicting him.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To have an interview with; especially, to make a
call upon; to visit; <as>as, to go to <ex>see</ex> a
friend</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And Samuel came no more to <qex>see</qex> Saul until the day of
his death.</q> <rj><qau>1 Sam. xv. 35.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To fall in with; to meet or associate with; to have
intercourse or communication with; hence, to have knowledge or
experience of; <as>as, to <ex>see</ex> military service</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Make us glad according to the days wherein thou hast afflicted us,
and the years wherein we have <qex>seen</qex> evil.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xc.
15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Verily, verily, I say unto you, if a man keep my saying, he shall
never <qex>see</qex> death.</q> <rj><qau>John viii. 51.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Improvement in wisdom and prudence by <qex>seeing</qex> men.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To accompany in person; to escort; to wait upon;
<as>as, to <ex>see</ex> one home; to <ex>see</ex> one aboard the
cars</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>In poker and similar games at cards, to meet (a
bet), or to equal the bet of (a player), by staking the same sum.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧I'll <ex>see</ex> you and raise you ten.⟦rdquo⟧⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>God you see</b></col> (<it>or</it> <col><b>God him
see</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>God me see</b></col>, etc.)</mcol>,
<cd>God keep you (him, me, etc.) in his sight; God protect you.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Chaucer.</au> -- <col><b>To see
<plain>(anything)</plain> out</b></col>, <cd>to see (it) to the end; to
be present at, work at, or attend, to the end.</cd> -- <col><b>To see
stars</b></col>, <cd>to see flashes of light, like stars; -- sometimes
the result of concussion of the head.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> --
<col><b>To see <plain>(one)</plain> through</b></col>, <cd>to help,
watch, or guard (one) to the end of a course or an
undertaking.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>See</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: See
<hw>See</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To have the power of
sight, or of perceiving by the proper organs; to possess or employ the
sense of vision; <as>as, he <ex>sees</ex> distinctly</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whereas I was blind, now I <qex>see</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>John ix.
25.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Figuratively: To have intellectual apprehension; to
perceive; to know; to understand; to discern; -- often followed by a
preposition, as <xex>through</xex>, or <xex>into</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For judgment I am come into this world, that they which
<qex>see</qex> not might <qex>see</qex>; and that they which
<qex>see</qex> might be made blind.</q> <rj><qau>John ix.
39.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Many sagacious persons will find us out, . . . and <qex>see</qex>
through all our fine pretensions.</q> <rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be attentive; to take care; to give heed; --
generally with <xex>to</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>see</ex> to the
house</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>See</qex> that ye fall not out by the way.</q> <rj><qau>Gen.
xlv. 24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Let me see</xex>, <xex>Let us see</xex>, are used
to express consideration, or to introduce the particular consideration
of a subject, or some scheme or calculation.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cassio's a proper man, <qex>let me see</qex> now, -⟦br⟧
To get his place.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>See</xex> is sometimes used in the imperative for
<xex>look</xex>, or <xex>behold</xex>. ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>See</xex>.
<xex>see</xex>! upon the banks of Boyne he stands.⟦rdquo⟧</note>
<rj><au>Halifax.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To see about a thing</b></col>, <cd>to pay attention to
it; to consider it.</cd> -- <col><b>To see on</b></col>, <cd>to look
at.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧She was full more blissful <xex>on
to see</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Chaucer.</au> -- <col><b>To see to</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To look at; to behold; to view</cd>.
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧An altar by Jordan, a great altar <xex>to see
to</xex>⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Josh. xxii. 10.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To take care
about; to look after; <as>as, <ex>to see to</ex> a
fire</as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seecatch</ent>⟦br⟧
